    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-02-13T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-02-13T00:00:00-05:00" n="833"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d833">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 882.00/443.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the <gloss type="to">American Minister</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 21.]</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-02-13">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 13, 1912</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: The Department has received your dispatch No. 25
                    (Diplomatic Series) of the 5th instant,<note n="1" xml:id="d833fn1">See
                        “Disturbances on the Sierra Leone-Liberia boundary,” <ref target="#pg_652"
                            >p. 652</ref>; the date above given is wrong; it should be January
                        8.</note> in which you transmit copies of correspondence concerning the
                    recent disturbances on the Sierra Leone-Liberian border, and suggest the
                    necessity for an early reorganization of the Liberian Frontier Force.</p>
                <p>In reply you are informed that Captain Charles Young, Ninth Cavalry, United
                    States Army, who has recently been designated as Military Attaché to your
                    Legation, expects to leave for Monrovia as soon as the loan agreement is signed
                    which, it is now anticipated, will be in the near future. The War Department has
                    selected three ex-Army officers who also expect to leave shortly for Monrovia to
                    take up their duties in connection with reorganizing the constabulary.</p>
                <p>I am [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Huntington Wilson.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
